376
00:33:31,200 --> 00:33:37,240
Kind of. Okay. The font that we use 
today is a modified version of Adelle  

377
00:33:37,240 --> 00:33:43,560
Sans. The story there is, I looked 
at all of the major font families,  

378
00:33:43,560 --> 00:33:49,640
and honestly none of them was what I would 
call truly excellent. That may sound like  

379
00:33:49,640 --> 00:33:55,280
an odd thing to say. So let's, if you will 
permit me to talk about typography and email-

380
00:33:56,480 --> 00:33:56,680
Please.

381
00:33:56,680 --> 00:34:03,160
The first thing we did was, we took our UI and 
we laid it out in about 15 different styles  

382
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:08,880
using examples of the major font families. We 
actually printed these out and we left them on  

383
00:34:08,880 --> 00:34:17,120
a desk in the middle of our office. Sometimes with 
design, you want to tune in to your immediate most  

384
00:34:17,120 --> 00:34:24,000
visceral response, but sometimes you want to 
truly let a design marinate. And this was the  

385
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:30,160
latter. So we let these designs marinate, we 
let these font choices percolate. Like I said,  

386
00:34:30,160 --> 00:34:33,720
none of them was truly excellent.
Number one, I was looking for a font  

387
00:34:33,720 --> 00:34:39,520
that was in and of itself gorgeous. Number two, 
I was looking for a font that could also convey  

388
00:34:39,520 --> 00:34:46,120
a message of any kind, without overpowering the 
sentiment of that message. For example, does the  

389
00:34:46,120 --> 00:34:51,840
font work when this is inviting you to a party? 
Many fonts, including almost all serif fonts,  

390
00:34:51,840 --> 00:34:57,640
are actually too somber or too sober for that. 
Or to pick another extreme, does the font work  

391
00:34:58,280 --> 00:35:04,400
if it is informing you of somebody's passing, many 
fonts are just too jaunty for that. You wouldn't  

392
00:35:04,400 --> 00:35:09,640
want that kind of message in Comic Sans, for 
example. And number three, I was optimizing for  

393
00:35:09,640 --> 00:35:15,760
a font that made reading speed and comprehension 
really fast. And number four, I was looking  

394
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:22,240
for a font that made email addresses themselves 
look great. So I discarded all the 15 because  

395
00:35:22,240 --> 00:35:27,640
they weren't good enough, and after searching high 
and low, I came across a font called Adelle Sans,  

396
00:35:28,400 --> 00:35:33,400
which is designed by a foundry called Type 
Together, type-together.com. They have a whole  

397
00:35:33,400 --> 00:35:37,960
bunch of lovely fonts, go check them out.
And if you go through my list, number one,  

398
00:35:37,960 --> 00:35:42,720
Adelle Sans is gorgeous. I think each character 
is a work of art. It's beautifully formed. Number  

399
00:35:42,720 --> 00:35:49,240
two, Adelle Sans is, I would say upbeat, it's 
optimistic, yet it's serious enough to convey any  

400
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:55,320
kind of message. It has just the right amount of 
personality, yet not too much personality. Number  

401
00:35:55,320 --> 00:36:02,240
three, Adelle Sans is also unusually narrow, 
and that actually fits email particularly well.  

402
00:36:02,240 --> 00:36:08,520
One of my pet peeves with Gmail, which by default 
uses Ariel, is that the lines are as wide as your  

403
00:36:08,520 --> 00:36:15,440
window. So if you're in a wide screen, then 
the lines get really arbitrarily long. The  

404
00:36:15,440 --> 00:36:19,920
problem with really wide and really long lines, 
is that they decrease reading speed. Because by  

405
00:36:19,920 --> 00:36:24,160
the time you've reached the end of one line, 
your eyes have lost track of the start of the  

406
00:36:24,160 --> 00:36:29,960
next line. And Ariel itself has fairly wide 
characters, which further exacerbates that. 

407
00:36:29,960 --> 00:36:34,880
So at Superhuman we, if you've used the product, 
you know this, we fix the line length or the  

408
00:36:34,880 --> 00:36:39,960
typographical measure to the optimal length for 
reading speed, which depending on the font is  

409
00:36:39,960 --> 00:36:47,400
around 90 to 120 characters. And Adelle Sans is 
quite narrow, so it actually lets us do this on  

410
00:36:47,400 --> 00:36:55,240
quite small windows with fairly dense line. So we 
get a lot of information on fairly small windows  

411
00:36:55,240 --> 00:37:00,120
without getting a very long typographical 
measure, optimizing for reading speed and  

412
00:37:00,120 --> 00:37:05,800
for comprehension. Then number four, finally 
Adelle Sans has very unusual treatment of the  

413
00:37:05,800 --> 00:37:12,440
at symbol in an email address. It actually 
puts the base of the A in the at on the  

414
00:37:12,440 --> 00:37:17,600
same baseline as the rest of the text.
So for example, if your name has an A,  

415
00:37:17,600 --> 00:37:24,320
my name does Rahul at Vohra, three A's and or 
two A's and an at, they're all actually on the  

416
00:37:24,320 --> 00:37:31,040
same baseline. It's a small thing, but it makes 
the email addresses look incredibly natural. If  

417
00:37:31,040 --> 00:37:34,720
you look at that and then you actually look 
at email addresses laid out in other fonts,  

418
00:37:34,720 --> 00:37:38,720
those other the fonts look really clunky and 
awkward because the A is kind of shifted around  

419
00:37:38,720 --> 00:37:43,600
and it just looks a bit silly in my opinion. 
Now Adelle Sans isn't perfect. So we then worked  

420
00:37:43,600 --> 00:37:47,960
with a type designer on some of the specific 
details that there are some of the glyphs,  

421
00:37:47,960 --> 00:37:55,240
which get a little pinchy as it were, and what 
we use today is very close to retail Adelle Sans.

422
00:37:55,240 --> 00:37:58,880
And this was pre-launch or this 
was after you'd already launched?

423
00:37:58,880 --> 00:38:03,360
We'd probably had about 10, 15 users at the time.

424
00:38:03,360 --> 00:38:09,520
So I think that's pretty contrarian unique to 
be this focused on the font and the typeface  

