00:38:09,520 --> 00:38:13,200
before you even launched. This was like, 
"Is this even going to be a thing? Will  

426
00:38:13,200 --> 00:38:17,880
anyone even care?" And I think this says a 
lot about the way you think about product.

427
00:38:17,880 --> 00:38:23,120
Oh yeah, that thought never crossed my mind. 
I think we'll probably come to it later,  

428
00:38:23,120 --> 00:38:30,400
but the idea that, is this never going to be a 
thing? I think that's a dangerous thought. We  

429
00:38:30,400 --> 00:38:35,680
can't start thinking that way, because at what 
point do you stop second-guessing yourself?

430
00:38:35,680 --> 00:38:41,040
Interesting. So you were confident this was going 
to work, so because I am so confident it'll work,  

431
00:38:41,040 --> 00:38:47,000
I need them to get this right. There's also 
this trap founders fall into of just spending  

432
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:51,640
too much time perfecting a thing that never 
works and there's always advice launch early,  

433
00:38:51,640 --> 00:38:57,520
launch often. Thoughts there? How do you 
find that balance? What's your advice there?

434
00:38:57,520 --> 00:39:04,760
How much to spend time ahead of launch really 
does depend on the markets and the structure,  

435
00:39:04,760 --> 00:39:11,280
the nature of your business model. For example, 
let's say you are building a marketplace in a  

436
00:39:11,280 --> 00:39:17,880
greenfield opportunity, so imagine the Lyft 
or Uber in their heyday. There's a strong  

437
00:39:17,880 --> 00:39:22,040
network effect, because the more cars you have 
on your platform, the shorter waiting times are,  

438
00:39:22,040 --> 00:39:27,520
therefore people are going to preferentially 
use your app versus the other person's app.  

439
00:39:27,520 --> 00:39:33,280
That's when there's no time to spare, that's when 
you probably shouldn't even be sleeping. You're  

440
00:39:33,280 --> 00:39:38,760
going to hire the most aggressive maniacal people 
possible. You're going to work 120-hour weeks,  

441
00:39:38,760 --> 00:39:46,200
because every marginal minute actually does 
matter. Every marginal minute in the market,  

442
00:39:46,200 --> 00:39:51,040
growing compounding is going to 
make your next year even better. 

443
00:39:51,040 --> 00:39:57,640
That's actually not true of all startups and it 
certainly isn't true of something like Superhuman.  

444
00:39:57,640 --> 00:40:04,200
Yes, working harder is always better and we work 
tremendously hard at Superhuman, but not to the  

445
00:40:04,200 --> 00:40:14,280
point where it made sense to release something 
that didn't work. I'm reminded of a story of a  

446
00:40:14,280 --> 00:40:22,840
founder that was in Y Combinator, told me about 
their demo day experience. They used Mailbox,  

447
00:40:22,840 --> 00:40:27,840
which some folks may remember was also a startup, 
and Dropbox famously acquired them for about  

448
00:40:27,840 --> 00:40:33,080
a hundred million dollars. The reason that they 
were well known, apart from the acquisition,  

449
00:40:33,080 --> 00:40:39,000
is they were the first to popularize, swipe to 
archive or swipe to mark down, which of course is  

450
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:47,640
now standard in Superhuman and every other app.
This founder was using Mailbox and was having  

451
00:40:47,640 --> 00:40:53,560
an amazing demo day. They're working the room, 
they're meeting investors, they're pitching their  

452
00:40:53,560 --> 00:41:01,120
photography app in this case. He went home that 
night and went to his laptop, fired up mailbox and  

453
00:41:01,120 --> 00:41:09,400
sent off a bunch of follow-up emails. He waited 
