and which reinforced our product strategy. 

488
00:44:13,280 --> 00:44:18,160
In the first year of Superhuman, therefore, I 
interviewed hundreds of potential customers about  

489
00:44:18,160 --> 00:44:23,760
their experience with Gmail and with Outlook. 
And predictably, almost everybody says that  

490
00:44:23,760 --> 00:44:31,560
email takes way too much time. But interestingly, 
many people also said that Gmail and Outlook were  

491
00:44:31,560 --> 00:44:38,280
way too slow. That was how I first thought 
that speed could be an interesting position  

492
00:44:38,280 --> 00:44:44,280
for us. I then asked myself, "Is the position 
of speed unique and is it available?" And the  

493
00:44:44,280 --> 00:44:50,400
answer was overwhelmingly yes, because almost 
no software was being sold or has ever been  

494
00:44:50,400 --> 00:44:57,600
sold on the value proposition of speed. The last 
time I could remember anyone trying to do this,  

495
00:44:57,600 --> 00:45:02,520
was when Google launched Chrome, and obviously 
that went incredibly well for them. You may  

496
00:45:02,520 --> 00:45:09,600
remember they had slow-motion videos where 
they were comparing Chrome render webpages and  

497
00:45:09,600 --> 00:45:16,000
showing that was faster than an actual strike 
of lightning. No one had done it since then. 

498
00:45:16,000 --> 00:45:20,560
I then asked, "Well, does speed reinforce 
our product strategy?" And again,  

499
00:45:20,560 --> 00:45:25,400
the answer was overwhelmingly yes. I knew that 
our competition was not going to be startups,  

500
00:45:25,400 --> 00:45:31,040
it was incumbents. And I also knew that 
incumbents generally struggle with speed,  

501
00:45:31,040 --> 00:45:38,080
because by definition they have massive scale and 
