sake of argument, that you can put a number  

606
00:55:09,120 --> 00:55:13,600
on product market fit, and it turns out you 
can. Very simply, you're going to ask people,  

607
00:55:13,600 --> 00:55:18,240
"How would you feel if you can no longer use this 
product?" You give them three responses. One of  

608
00:55:18,240 --> 00:55:23,360
them is very disappointed, the other is somewhat 
disappointed, and the other is not disappointed.  

609
00:55:23,360 --> 00:55:30,000
Very disappointed means, "I'd be devastated. 
I love this product. I need this product." 

610
00:55:30,000 --> 00:55:36,000
What Sean Ellis found, Sean Ellis, if you don't 
know him, is the guy who coined the term growth  

611
00:55:36,000 --> 00:55:41,680
hacker, and he instrumented, benchmarked 
this initial question. What he found,  

612
00:55:41,680 --> 00:55:47,120
is that the companies that struggled to 
grow almost always had less than 40%,  

613
00:55:47,120 --> 00:55:52,440
very disappointed. Whereas the companies that 
grew the fastest almost always had more than 40%,  

614
00:55:52,440 --> 00:56:00,840
very disappointed. And this question, this metric 
is way more predictive of success than something,  

615
00:56:00,840 --> 00:56:07,760
for example, like net promoter score.
Okay, so far so easy. How do we make  

616
00:56:07,760 --> 00:56:15,840
this number go up? Well, you want more people to 
be very disappointed without your product. The  

617
00:56:15,840 --> 00:56:22,200
trick here is not to act too much on the feedback 
that the very disappointed people are giving you,  

618
00:56:22,200 --> 00:56:27,240
because they already love your product. Also, not 
to act at all really on the feedback that the not  

619
00:56:27,240 --> 00:56:30,320
disappointed people are giving, you because 
they're so far from loving your product that  

620
00:56:30,320 --> 00:56:37,440
they're essentially a lost cause. But to focus on 
the segment of the somewhat disappointed people,  

621
00:56:37,440 --> 00:56:39,880
they kind of love your product, 
but something, and I would wager  

622
00:56:39,880 --> 00:56:45,320
something small, is holding them back.
You then divide them into two camps,  

623
00:56:45,320 --> 00:56:50,120
the camp for whom the main benefit of your product 
resonates and the camp for whom it doesn't. What  

624
00:56:50,120 --> 00:56:54,200
do I mean by that? Well, you go back to the people 
who really love your product and you basically ask  

625
00:56:54,200 --> 00:56:58,920
them why? What is it about my products that you 
really love? In the early days of Superhuman,  

626
00:56:58,920 --> 00:57:03,360
it would have been speed and keyboard shortcuts 
