663
01:00:05,040 --> 01:00:11,360
when we make products like we make games, people 
find them fun. They tell their friends, they fall  

664
01:00:11,360 --> 01:00:16,600
in love with them. It's another way actually of 
backing into where we open this conversation,  

665
01:00:16,600 --> 01:00:20,920
which is you're making a brand, you are giving 
reason for word of mouth. It's actually an  

666
01:00:20,920 --> 01:00:27,320
altogether different kind of product development. 
So how do we do this? Well, as you've said,  

667
01:00:27,320 --> 01:00:33,800
it's not gamification, that doesn't work. Game 
design works, but game design is not gamification.  

668
01:00:33,800 --> 01:00:40,560
It's not, for example, simply taking your product 
and adding points, levels, trophies or badges. 

669
01:00:40,560 --> 01:00:46,680
To understand why gamification does not work, 
we actually have to start with human motivation.  

670
01:00:46,680 --> 01:00:52,720
There's a very interesting study from Stanford 
that demonstrates the difference perfectly. In  

671
01:00:52,720 --> 01:00:58,840
the 1970s, these Stanford researchers recruited 
children who were aged three to four years old,  

672
01:00:58,840 --> 01:01:05,551
and all of these kids were generally 
pre-interested in drawing. Some kids  

673
01:01:05,551 --> 01:01:08,280
were told they would get a reward, a certificate 
with a gold seal and a ribbon. And some kids were  

674
01:01:08,280 --> 01:01:13,040
not told about any reward and they did not 
even expect one or didn't know of one. Now  

675
01:01:13,040 --> 01:01:18,760
each child was then invited into a separate 
room to draw for six minutes and afterwards  

676
01:01:18,760 --> 01:01:24,760
they would either get the reward or not.
Over the next few days, the children were observed  

677
01:01:24,760 --> 01:01:31,040
to see how much they would continue to draw 
by themselves. So the children with no reward,  

678
01:01:31,040 --> 01:01:39,480
they spent 17% of their time drawing, but the 
children who expected a reward, sadly they  

679
01:01:39,480 --> 01:01:46,840
only spent 8% of their time drawing. The very 
presence of a reward halved their motivation.  

680
01:01:46,840 --> 01:01:52,440
So what's happening? What's happening here, is 
researchers differentiate intrinsic motivation  

681
01:01:52,440 --> 01:01:56,920
and extrinsic motivation. With intrinsic 
motivation we do things because they are  

682
01:01:56,920 --> 01:02:02,600
inherently interesting and satisfying, and with 
extrinsic motivation, we do things to earn rewards  

683
01:02:02,600 --> 01:02:08,080
and to achieve external goals. That's the problem 
with rewards, is they just massively undermine  

684
01:02:08,080 --> 01:02:13,520
intrinsic motivation. That's why gamification 
doesn't work. And when gamification does work,  

685
01:02:13,520 --> 01:02:19,080
it's because the underlying experience 
was already designed like a game.

686
01:02:19,080 --> 01:02:23,240
What makes something like a game? I 
know Superhuman is really good at this,  

687
01:02:23,240 --> 01:02:28,000
of just your inbox zero quest that you're 
on. Just to make that a little more real,  

688
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:32,040
what is game design? What does that mean 
