868
01:19:22,680 --> 01:19:28,920
SDR is a thinking tool that I picked 
up from Reid Hoffman during my time at  

869
01:19:28,920 --> 01:19:36,080
LinkedIn. The idea here is that for important 
decisions, you should be able to identify one,  

870
01:19:36,080 --> 01:19:43,040
one reason that on its own supports the decision. 
It's based on the observation that all too often  

871
01:19:43,040 --> 01:19:49,360
we rely on a collection of weak reasons to 
justify decisions. It's very, very easy to do  

872
01:19:49,360 --> 01:19:55,080
this. Imagine you are contemplating a decision, 
you write a list of the pros and the cons.  

873
01:19:55,080 --> 01:20:00,680
There are three pros, but let's say there 
are 10 or 15 cons. The sheer number of cons,  

874
01:20:00,680 --> 01:20:05,720
the effort of thinking them through, the time it 
took to write them down, is going to affect you,  

875
01:20:05,720 --> 01:20:11,800
consciously or worse subconsciously. This is 
especially true, I've seen in group settings,  

876
01:20:11,800 --> 01:20:17,040
which just in general are a little bit more risk 
averse and a little bit more consensus driven. 

877
01:20:17,040 --> 01:20:24,240
So whenever anyone is making a decision and 
they bring that decision to me and they say,  

878
01:20:24,240 --> 01:20:28,120
"Well, we want to do this because of X, Y, Z, 
and there are multiple reasons." I ask them,  

879
01:20:28,120 --> 01:20:34,520
"What's the SDR? What's the single decisive 
reason?" If they can't yet isolate it,  

880
01:20:34,520 --> 01:20:38,160
that tells me they haven't yet figured out why 
they want to make the decision. It doesn't mean  

881
01:20:38,160 --> 01:20:43,280
the decision is wrong, it just means that they 
haven't figured out the singular reason why we  

882
01:20:43,280 --> 01:20:49,560
should do the thing. They can then go through 
their list of reasons and ask, "Is this alone  

883
01:20:49,560 --> 01:20:52,680
enough to support this decision?" Meaning if this 
was true and all the other things were not true,  

884
01:20:52,680 --> 01:20:58,520
would I still do it? And sometimes we still 
do, but actually sometimes we don't. We realize  

885
01:20:58,520 --> 01:21:04,800
that a collection of weak reasons alone means 
that, for example, the outcome is less likely  

886
01:21:04,800 --> 01:21:11,480
than we thought it was, or it was hiding a really 
strong reason on the other side of the decision.

